    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Who Needs Portable DVD?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Ira Rosofsky letter says laptop with DVD movie capacity makes more sense than dedicated portable DVD player (July 27 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The need for a dedicated portable DVD player escapes me (''DVD's Move to the Really Small Screen,'' July 27). For just a bit more money, you can get a full-fledged laptop computer with a DVD player and a screen twice as large. On my Dell portable, for instance, I can watch ''Chinatown'' in one window while I have a chess game going in another and write this letter to you in a third. Why would I want a device that does only one thing not even as well as a computer that does many things -- unless I'm of the class that must have the latest but not necessarily the greatest?</p>
        <p>IRA ROSOFSKY  New Haven, Conn.</p>
      </block>
